abstract = {The 23 Glazer tilt systems describing octahedral tilting in perovskites have been investigated. The various tilt systems have been compared in terms of their {\it A}-cation coordination and it is shown that those tilt systems in which all the {\it A}-cation sites remain crystallographically equivalent are strongly favored, when all the {\it A} sites are occupied by the same ion. Calculations based on both ionic and covalent models have been performed to compare the seven equivalent {\it A}-site tilt systems. Both methods predict that when the tilt angles become large, the orthorhombic {\it a}${\sp +}${\it b}${\sp {$-$}}${\it b}${\sp {$-$}}$ tilt system will result in the lowest energy structure. This tilt system gives the lowest energy structure because it maximizes the number of short {\it A}{---}O interactions. The rhombohedral {\it a}${\sp {$-$}}${\it a}${\sp {$-$}}${\it a}${\sp {$-$}}$ tilt system gives a structure with a slightly lower Madelung energy, but increased ion{--}ion repulsions destabilize this structure as the tilt angles increase. Consequently, it is stabilized by highly charged {\it A} cations and small to moderate tilt angles. The ideal cubic {\it a}${\sp 0}${\it a}${\sp 0}${\it a}${\sp 0}$ tilt system is only observed when stabilized by oversized {\it A} cations and/or {\it M}{---}O {$\pi$}-bonding. Tilt systems with nonequivalent {\it A}-site environments are observed when at least two {\it A} cations with different sizes and/or bonding preferences are present. In these compounds the ratio of large-to-small cations dictates the most stable tilt system.},
